## What happened

In .NET 11, **DSA support was removed from macOS**. Calling `DSA.Create()` (or any DSA signing/verification) now **throws at runtime** on macOS. Windows and Linux are unaffected.

## How to fix it

Since you need to **verify legacy DSA signatures**, you can't simply switch the signing algorithm. Your options:

1. **Run DSA verification only on Linux/Windows.** Gate the code with a runtime check:
   ```csharp
   if (OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())
       throw new PlatformNotSupportedException("DSA verification not supported on macOS in .NET 11+");
   ```

2. **Use a cross-platform crypto library** (e.g., [BouncyCastle](https://www.nuget.org/packages/BouncyCastle.Cryptography)) that provides its own DSA implementation independent of the OS:
   ```csharp
   // Using BouncyCastle for DSA verification on all platforms
   var verifier = SignerUtilities.GetSigner("SHA256withDSA");
   verifier.Init(false, publicKey);
   verifier.BlockUpdate(data, 0, data.Length);
   bool valid = verifier.VerifySignature(signature);
   ```

3. **Drop macOS as a target** if DSA verification is a hard requirement and a third-party library isn't acceptable.

**Recommendation:** Option 2 (BouncyCastle) is the best path — it keeps all three platforms working and lets you continue verifying existing DSA signatures without re-signing anything.
